(28, 1, 'TSH - THYROID STIMULATING HORMONE', 'EXP0028', '399', '199', 'Same day', 'Fasting not mandatory', 'Fasting not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TSH, or thyroid-stimulating hormone, is produced by the pituitary gland. It regulates thyroid function by stimulating the thyroid gland to produce hormones T3 and T4. TSH levels are measured to diagnose thyroid disorders such as hypothyroidism and hyperthyroidism, helping to assess thyroid function and guide treatment.', NULL, '<p>Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) is a hormone produced by the pituitary gland that plays a critical role in regulating the thyroid gland\'s function. TSH stimulates the thyroid to produce and release thyroid hormones, primarily thyroxine (T4) and triiodothyronine (T3), which are essential for regulating metabolism, energy levels, and overall growth and development. The levels of TSH in the blood are a key indicator of thyroid health.</p><p>When TSH levels are elevated, it typically indicates hypothyroidism, a condition where the thyroid is underactive and not producing enough thyroid hormones. Conversely, low TSH levels suggest hyperthyroidism, where the thyroid is overactive and producing excess hormones.</p><p>Measuring TSH is crucial for diagnosing thyroid disorders and for monitoring the effectiveness of treatments for conditions like hypothyroidism and hyperthyroidism. Regular TSH testing helps ensure that thyroid hormone levels remain balanced, supporting optimal metabolic function and overall health.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-12 17:12:14', '2024-07-12 17:14:00', NULL, 0),
(29, 1, 'TFT - Thyroid Profile', 'EXP0029', '699', '399', 'Same day', 'Fasting not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Thyroid function tests (TFTs) assess thyroid health by measuring hormones like TSH, T3, and T4 in the blood. These tests help diagnose thyroid disorders such as hypothyroidism and hyperthyroidism, monitor treatment efficacy, and ensure proper thyroid hormone balance for optimal metabolic function and overall health.', 'Weight loss & Gain', '<h4>&nbsp;</h4><p>Thyroid function tests (TFTs) are a group of blood tests used to evaluate the thyroid gland’s health and its hormone production. The thyroid gland produces hormones crucial for regulating metabolism, energy levels, and overall growth and development. The primary hormones measured in TFTs include thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH), thyroxine (T4), and triiodothyronine (T3).</p><p>TSH is produced by the pituitary gland and stimulates the thyroid to produce T4 and T3. Measuring TSH levels is a key indicator of thyroid function. High TSH levels typically suggest hypothyroidism, where the thyroid is underactive. Low TSH levels indicate hyperthyroidism, where the thyroid is overactive.</p><p>T4 and T3 are the main hormones produced by the thyroid. T4 is the primary hormone circulating in the blood, while T3 is the more active form. Both are essential for maintaining metabolic rate, heart and digestive functions, muscle control, brain development, and bone health.</p><p>In addition to these hormones, TFTs may include tests for thyroid antibodies to help diagnose autoimmune thyroid diseases like Hashimoto’s thyroiditis and Graves’ disease.</p><p>TFTs are crucial for diagnosing thyroid disorders, monitoring treatment efficacy, and guiding therapy adjustments. By ensuring proper thyroid hormone levels, TFTs help maintain optimal metabolic function and overall health. Regular testing is particularly important for individuals with known thyroid conditions or those experiencing symptoms like fatigue, weight changes, or mood disturbances.<br>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>Test Parameters -: 3 Parameters&nbsp;</p>', '2024-07-12 17:56:01', '2024-07-12 17:56:25', NULL, 0),
(30, 1, 'Anti TG, ATG- Any Thyroglobulin Antibody', 'EXP0030', '1300', '699', 'Same day', 'Fasting not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Anti-thyroglobulin antibodies are immune proteins that target thyroglobulin, a protein produced by the thyroid gland. Elevated levels of these antibodies can indicate autoimmune thyroid disorders, such as Hashimoto\'s thyroiditis or Graves\' disease. Measuring these antibodies helps diagnose and monitor these conditions.', NULL, '<p>Anti-thyroglobulin antibodies (TgAb) are proteins produced by the immune system that target thyroglobulin, a protein essential for thyroid hormone production. Elevated levels of TgAb in the blood indicate autoimmune thyroid diseases, particularly Hashimoto’s thyroiditis and sometimes Graves’ disease.</p><p>Hashimoto’s thyroiditis is characterized by inflammation and destruction of thyroid tissue, leading to hypothyroidism. TgAb levels are often elevated in this condition as the immune system mistakenly attacks thyroglobulin and thyroid cells. In Graves’ disease, TgAb levels can also be elevated, although the main antibodies involved are thyroid-stimulating immunoglobulins (TSI), which stimulate the thyroid gland to produce excess hormones.</p><p>Measuring TgAb helps diagnose autoimmune thyroid disorders and distinguish them from other thyroid conditions. It also assists in monitoring disease progression and response to treatment. High TgAb levels may indicate ongoing autoimmune activity, while declining levels can signify treatment effectiveness or disease remission.</p><p>Monitoring TgAb alongside other thyroid function tests is crucial for managing autoimmune thyroid diseases, ensuring appropriate treatment adjustments, and preventing complications related to thyroid hormone imbalances.</p>', '<h4>Parameters includes :- 1 &nbsp;Test</h4>', '2024-07-12 18:05:54', '2024-07-12 18:05:54', NULL, 0),
(31, 1, 'Anti  TPO - Anti Thyroid Peroxide Antibody -AMA', 'EXP0031', '1599', '699', 'Same day', 'Fasting not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Anti-TPO (thyroid peroxidase antibodies) are immune proteins that target thyroid peroxidase, an enzyme involved in thyroid hormone production. Elevated levels of anti-TPO antibodies in the blood indicate autoimmune thyroid disorders, such as Hashimoto\'s thyroiditis and Graves\' disease, aiding in diagnosis and monitoring of these conditions.', NULL, '<p>Anti-TPO (thyroid peroxidase antibodies) are antibodies produced by the immune system that target thyroid peroxidase, an enzyme crucial for the production of thyroid hormones thyroxine (T4) and triiodothyronine (T3). Thyroid peroxidase is involved in the iodination and coupling reactions necessary for thyroid hormone synthesis.</p><p>Elevated levels of anti-TPO antibodies in the blood are indicative of autoimmune thyroid diseases, particularly Hashimoto’s thyroiditis and sometimes Graves’ disease. In Hashimoto’s thyroiditis, the immune system mistakenly attacks and damages the thyroid gland, leading to inflammation and eventual hypothyroidism. Anti-TPO antibodies are often present in high levels in this condition, reflecting ongoing autoimmune activity against thyroid tissue.</p><p>In Graves’ disease, while the primary antibodies involved are thyroid-stimulating immunoglobulins (TSI), anti-TPO antibodies can also be elevated, indicating autoimmune involvement in this hyperthyroid condition.</p><p>Measuring anti-TPO antibodies helps diagnose autoimmune thyroid disorders, distinguish them from other forms of thyroid disease, and monitor disease progression and response to treatment. High levels of anti-TPO antibodies may fluctuate over time but generally persist in autoimmune thyroid diseases, providing valuable diagnostic and prognostic information for clinicians managing thyroid health.</p>', '<p>Parameters Includes :- 1 Test&nbsp;</p>', '2024-07-12 18:14:13', '2024-07-12 18:14:13', NULL, 0),
(32, 1, 'Anti TG &  Anti TPO - Anti Thyroid Antibodies panel', 'EXP0032', '2799', '1399', 'Same day repoy', 'Fasting not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Anti-TG (anti-thyroglobulin antibodies) and anti-TPO (anti-thyroid peroxidase antibodies) are immune proteins that target proteins in the thyroid gland. Elevated levels of these antibodies in the blood indicate autoimmune thyroid diseases such as Hashimoto\'s thyroiditis and Graves\' disease. They are crucial for diagnosing these conditions and monitoring disease activity. Anti-TG targets thyroglobulin, a protein involved in thyroid hormone production, while anti-TPO targets thyroid peroxidase, an enzyme essential for thyroid hormone synthesis.', NULL, '<p>An anti-thyroid antibodies panel typically includes tests for anti-thyroglobulin antibodies (anti-TG) and anti-thyroid peroxidase antibodies (anti-TPO). These antibodies are markers of autoimmune thyroid diseases, which occur when the immune system mistakenly attacks the thyroid gland.</p><p>Anti-Thyroglobulin Antibodies (Anti-TG): Thyroglobulin is a protein produced by the thyroid gland as a precursor to thyroid hormones. Anti-TG antibodies target thyroglobulin, and elevated levels are associated with autoimmune thyroid conditions, particularly Hashimoto’s thyroiditis. This disease involves chronic inflammation of the thyroid gland, leading to hypothyroidism (underactive thyroid).</p><p>Anti-Thyroid Peroxidase Antibodies (Anti-TPO): Thyroid peroxidase is an enzyme crucial for thyroid hormone synthesis, aiding in iodine oxidation and coupling reactions. Anti-TPO antibodies target thyroid peroxidase, and elevated levels are also linked to autoimmune thyroid diseases, including Hashimoto’s thyroiditis and Graves’ disease. Graves’ disease is characterized by an overactive thyroid (hyperthyroidism), often accompanied by symptoms like weight loss, rapid heartbeat, and anxiety.</p><p>The anti-thyroid antibodies panel is essential for diagnosing autoimmune thyroid disorders, distinguishing them from other thyroid conditions, and guiding treatment decisions. High levels of anti-TG and/or anti-TPO antibodies indicate ongoing autoimmune activity against the thyroid gland. Regular monitoring of these antibodies helps assess disease progression, treatment response, and the likelihood of developing thyroid dysfunction.</p><p>In summary, the anti-thyroid antibodies panel plays a crucial role in the comprehensive evaluation of thyroid health, providing valuable diagnostic insights and aiding in the management of autoimmune thyroid diseases to optimize patient care and outcomes.</p>', '<h4>Parameters Includes :- 2 Test</h4>', '2024-07-12 18:49:19', '2024-07-12 18:49:19', NULL, 0),
(33, 1, 'Free Thyroid profile- FT 3 FT4 TSH', 'EXP0033', '999', '499', 'Same day', 'Fasting not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FT3 (Free Triiodothyronine) and FT4 (Free Thyroxine) are thyroid hormones circulating freely in the bloodstream. They regulate metabolism, growth, and energy levels. TSH (Thyroid-Stimulating Hormone) is produced by the pituitary gland to stimulate thyroid hormone production. High TSH suggests hypothyroidism (underactive thyroid), while low TSH indicates hyperthyroidism (overactive thyroid). FT3 and FT4 levels help diagnose and monitor thyroid disorders, guiding treatment adjustments to maintain hormone balance and overall health.', NULL, '<p>A free thyroid profile typically includes measurements of Free Triiodothyronine (FT3), Free Thyroxine (FT4), and Thyroid-Stimulating Hormone (TSH). FT3 and FT4 are thyroid hormones that circulate in the bloodstream unbound to proteins, representing the biologically active forms of thyroxine and triiodothyronine. These hormones are essential for regulating metabolism, growth, and energy expenditure throughout the body.</p><p>FT3 (Free Triiodothyronine): FT3 is the active form of thyroid hormone that affects cellular metabolism, protein synthesis, and the body’s sensitivity to other hormones.</p><p>FT4 (Free Thyroxine): FT4 is the precursor to FT3 and primarily responsible for maintaining metabolic rate, heart and digestive functions, muscle control, brain development, and bone health.</p><p>TSH (Thyroid-Stimulating Hormone): TSH is produced by the pituitary gland to regulate thyroid hormone production. Elevated TSH levels typically indicate hypothyroidism (underactive thyroid), whereas low TSH levels suggest hyperthyroidism (overactive thyroid).</p><p>A free thyroid profile is crucial for diagnosing thyroid disorders, including hypothyroidism, hyperthyroidism, and thyroid hormone resistance syndromes. It helps clinicians assess thyroid function accurately, monitor treatment efficacy, and adjust medication dosages as needed to maintain hormonal balance and support overall health. Regular testing of FT3, FT4, and TSH is essential for managing thyroid conditions effectively and preventing complications related to thyroid hormone imbalances.</p>', '<h4>Parameters Includes :- 3 Tests</h4>', '2024-07-12 18:54:20', '2024-07-12 18:54:20', NULL, 0),
(34, 1, 'FT3- F Triiodothyronine', 'EXP0034', '449', '199', 'Same day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The FT3 test measures the levels of Free Triiodothyronine, the active form of thyroid hormone circulating in the bloodstream. FT3 plays a crucial role in regulating metabolism, energy production, and overall cellular function. Abnormal FT3 levels can indicate thyroid disorders such as hyperthyroidism or hypothyroidism.', NULL, '<p>Free Triiodothyronine (FT3) is a critical thyroid hormone that plays a pivotal role in regulating metabolism, energy production, and various physiological processes in the body. Unlike Total Triiodothyronine (T3), which includes both bound and unbound forms, FT3 specifically measures the biologically active form that is not bound to proteins and is readily available to enter cells and exert its effects.</p><p>FT3 influences metabolic rate, protein synthesis, and the body\'s sensitivity to other hormones. It affects almost every organ system, including the heart, digestive system, muscles, bones, and the central nervous system. FT3 levels are tightly regulated by the hypothalamus, pituitary gland, and thyroid gland through a complex feedback mechanism involving Thyroid-Stimulating Hormone (TSH).</p><p>Abnormal FT3 levels can indicate thyroid dysfunction. Elevated FT3 may suggest hyperthyroidism (overactive thyroid), characterized by symptoms such as weight loss, rapid heartbeat, and heat intolerance. Conversely, low FT3 levels may indicate hypothyroidism (underactive thyroid), leading to symptoms like fatigue, weight gain, and cold intolerance.</p><p>Measuring FT3 is crucial for diagnosing thyroid disorders, monitoring treatment effectiveness, and adjusting medication dosages to maintain optimal thyroid function and overall health.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-12 19:18:49', '2024-07-22 18:28:15', NULL, 0),
(35, 1, 'FT4 - F Thyroxine', 'EXP0035', '349', '199', 'Same day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FT4, or Free Thyroxine, is the active form of thyroid hormone that circulates freely in the bloodstream. It plays a critical role in regulating metabolism, growth, and energy levels throughout the body. Abnormal FT4 levels can indicate thyroid disorders such as hypothyroidism or hyperthyroidism.', NULL, '<p>The FT4 test measures Free Thyroxine, the active form of thyroid hormone that circulates freely in the bloodstream and is essential for regulating metabolism, growth, and energy levels. Unlike Total Thyroxine (T4), which includes both bound and unbound forms, FT4 specifically measures the biologically active fraction that is readily available to enter cells and exert its effects.</p><p>FT4 levels are influenced by the hypothalamus, pituitary gland, and thyroid gland through a feedback loop involving Thyroid-Stimulating Hormone (TSH). Elevated FT4 levels may indicate hyperthyroidism, where the thyroid gland is overactive, leading to symptoms such as weight loss, rapid heartbeat, and heat intolerance. Conversely, low FT4 levels may suggest hypothyroidism, characterized by symptoms like fatigue, weight gain, and cold intolerance.</p><p>The FT4 test is crucial for diagnosing thyroid disorders, monitoring thyroid function, and guiding treatment decisions. It helps differentiate between primary thyroid disorders and other conditions affecting thyroid hormone levels. Regular monitoring of FT4 levels is essential for individuals with thyroid conditions to ensure optimal management and adjustment of medication dosages to maintain thyroid hormone balance and overall health.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-12 19:20:47', '2024-07-22 18:37:53', NULL, 0),
(36, 1, 'Thyroid profile plus', 'EXP0036', '2999', '1299', 'Next day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FT3 (Free Triiodothyronine) and FT4 (Free Thyroxine) are active thyroid hormones crucial for metabolism. TSH (Thyroid-Stimulating Hormone) regulates thyroid hormone production. Elevated TSH suggests hypothyroidism, low TSH indicates hyperthyroidism. Anti-TPO (Anti-Thyroid Peroxidase Antibodies) indicate autoimmune thyroid diseases like Hashimoto\'s thyroiditis. Monitoring these markers aids in diagnosing and managing thyroid disorders effectively.', NULL, '<p>Anti-TPO (Anti-Thyroid Peroxidase Antibodies) are antibodies that target thyroid peroxidase, an enzyme essential for thyroid hormone production. Elevated Anti-TPO levels indicate autoimmune thyroid diseases such as Hashimoto\'s thyroiditis and Graves\' disease.</p><p>FT3 (Free Triiodothyronine) and FT4 (Free Thyroxine) are active thyroid hormones. FT3 influences metabolism and cellular functions, while FT4 primarily regulates metabolic rate and overall physiological functions.</p><p>TSH (Thyroid-Stimulating Hormone) is produced by the pituitary gland to stimulate thyroid hormone production. Elevated TSH levels indicate hypothyroidism (underactive thyroid), while low TSH levels suggest hyperthyroidism (overactive thyroid).</p><p>Combining measurements of Anti-TPO antibodies with FT3, FT4, and TSH levels provides a comprehensive assessment of thyroid function and autoimmune thyroid disorders. High Anti-TPO antibodies indicate autoimmune thyroid disease, affecting thyroid hormone production. FT3 and FT4 levels indicate the active hormone status, influencing metabolism, growth, and energy levels. TSH levels regulate thyroid hormone production, reflecting the pituitary gland\'s feedback on thyroid activity. Together, these tests aid in diagnosing thyroid disorders, monitoring treatment effectiveness, and guiding management strategies to maintain optimal thyroid hormone balance and overall health. Regular monitoring of these markers is crucial for individuals with thyroid conditions to ensure timely intervention and appropriate management.</p>', '<h4>Parameters includes :- 4 &nbsp;tests</h4>', '2024-07-12 19:26:43', '2024-07-12 19:27:06', NULL, 0),
(37, 1, 'TSH Receptor Antibody', 'EXP0037', '6999', '3499', 'Within 4 Days', 'Fasting not required', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The TSH receptor antibody test identifies antibodies targeting thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) receptors on the thyroid gland. Elevated levels indicate autoimmune thyroid diseases like Graves\' disease, where the thyroid overproduces hormones. This test helps diagnose and manage thyroid disorders by assessing autoimmune activity affecting thyroid function.', NULL, '<p>The TSH receptor antibody test measures antibodies that target the thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) receptors on cells in the thyroid gland. These antibodies are primarily associated with autoimmune thyroid diseases, particularly Graves\' disease. In Graves\' disease, these antibodies stimulate the TSH receptors, leading to excessive production of thyroid hormones (hyperthyroidism).</p><p>The test is crucial for diagnosing Graves\' disease and distinguishing it from other causes of hyperthyroidism. Elevated TSH receptor antibody levels confirm autoimmune activity against the thyroid gland, influencing hormone production and metabolic function.</p><p>Monitoring TSH receptor antibodies helps assess disease activity, guide treatment decisions, and monitor response to therapy. Treatment for Graves\' disease may involve medications to suppress thyroid hormone production, radioactive iodine therapy to reduce thyroid function, or in severe cases, surgical removal of the thyroid gland.</p><p>Regular testing and monitoring of TSH receptor antibodies are essential for managing Graves\' disease effectively and preventing complications related to excessive thyroid hormone levels, such as heart problems and bone loss. The test plays a crucial role in the comprehensive evaluation and management of autoimmune thyroid disorders, ensuring appropriate care and improved quality of life for affected individuals.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-12 19:32:38', '2024-07-12 19:32:38', NULL, 0),
(38, 1, 'PTH-Intact Parathyroid Hormone', 'EXP0038', '1499', '749', 'Same day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', 'Fasting sample to be given between 8-10 AM', '3ml ( 1.5 momin. ) serum from 1. SSTdrawn between 8-10am in a fasting condition', NULL, NULL, 'Parathyroid hormone (PTH) test measures levels of PTH in blood to assess parathyroid gland function. PTH regulates calcium and phosphorus levels in the body, crucial for bone health and nerve function. Abnormal PTH levels can indicate conditions like hyperparathyroidism or hypoparathyroidism, guiding diagnosis and treatment.', NULL, '<p>The parathyroid hormone (PTH) test measures the level of PTH in the blood, which is produced by the parathyroid glands located near the thyroid gland. PTH plays a crucial role in regulating calcium and phosphorus levels in the body, which are essential for bone health, nerve function, and muscle contractions.</p><p>PTH secretion is tightly regulated by calcium levels in the blood. When calcium levels are low, the parathyroid glands release PTH to increase calcium absorption from the intestines, release calcium from bones, and reduce calcium excretion by the kidneys. Conversely, high calcium levels suppress PTH production to maintain calcium homeostasis.</p><p>Abnormal PTH levels can indicate various disorders:</p><p>1. **Hyperparathyroidism**: Elevated PTH levels due to overactivity of the parathyroid glands. This can lead to excessive calcium levels in the blood (hypercalcemia), causing symptoms such as bone pain, kidney stones, fatigue, and abdominal pain.</p><p>2. **Hypoparathyroidism**: Low PTH levels due to underactivity or removal of the parathyroid glands. This results in low calcium levels in the blood (hypocalcemia), leading to muscle cramps, tingling sensations, seizures, and potentially life-threatening complications.</p><p>The PTH test helps diagnose and monitor these conditions, guiding treatment decisions. Treatment for hyperparathyroidism may involve surgery to remove the affected gland, medications to lower calcium levels, or management of underlying causes. Hypoparathyroidism is managed with calcium and vitamin D supplements to maintain normal calcium levels.</p><p>Regular monitoring of PTH levels is crucial for managing parathyroid disorders effectively and preventing complications related to abnormal calcium metabolism.</p>', '<p>पैरेथायड हार्मोन (PTH) एक हार्मोन है जो पैरेथायड ग्रंथियों द्वारा उत्पादित होता है, जो गर्दन में थायरॉयड ग्रंथि के पीछे स्थित होती हैं। PTH रक्त और हड्डियों में कैल्शियम स्तर को नियंत्रित करने में महत्वपूर्ण भूमिका निभाता है। यह हड्डियों से कैल्शियम की रिलीज को उत्तेजित करके, आंत्र में कैल्शियम के अवशोषण को बढ़ाकर, और किडनी में कैल्शियम की पुनरवशोषण को बढ़ाकर रक्त कैल्शियम स्तर को बढ़ाता है, जबकि फास्फेट को निकालता है। PTH हड्डियों के स्वास्थ्य और कैल्शियम संतुलन को बनाए रखने के लिए आवश्यक है।</p><p>PTH परीक्षण रक्त में इस हार्मोन के स्तर को मापता है ताकि पैरेथायड ग्रंथि के कार्य का आकलन किया जा सके। असामान्य PTH स्तर विभिन्न स्थितियों का संकेत दे सकते हैं, जैसे प्राथमिक या द्वितीयक हाइपरपैरेथायडिज़्म, हाइपोपैरेथायडिज़्म, या कैल्शियम मेटाबोलिज़्म से संबंधित समस्याएँ। यह परीक्षण इन स्थितियों का निदान करने और उचित उपचार मार्गदर्शित करने में मदद करता है, विशेषकर जब कैल्शियम या हड्डी के स्वास्थ्य की समस्याएँ उपस्थित हों।</p>', '2024-07-12 19:39:26', '2024-07-22 18:41:38', NULL, 0),
(39, 2, 'Urine Protein Creatinine Ratio', 'EXP0039', '499', '349', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The urine protein-to-creatinine ratio (UPCR) measures the amount of protein and creatinine in a urine sample, providing an estimate of daily protein excretion. It\'s a key test for detecting and monitoring kidney disease. Elevated UPCR levels indicate proteinuria, which can suggest kidney damage or dysfunction. The test is less influenced by urine concentration variations, making it a reliable method for assessing kidney health and function in both acute and chronic conditions.', NULL, '<p>The urine protein-to-creatinine ratio (UPCR) is a diagnostic test that measures the concentration of protein and creatinine in a single urine sample to estimate the amount of protein excreted in the urine over 24 hours. This ratio provides a reliable and convenient method for assessing kidney function and detecting kidney disease.</p><p>Proteinuria, or the presence of excess protein in the urine, is a common indicator of kidney damage. Normally, kidneys filter waste while retaining essential proteins in the bloodstream. However, when the kidneys are damaged or diseased, they may allow proteins to leak into the urine. The UPCR is calculated by dividing the urine protein concentration (mg/dL) by the urine creatinine concentration (mg/dL). Creatinine is a waste product from muscle metabolism, and its relatively constant excretion rate makes it a useful reference for assessing protein levels.</p><p>A high UPCR indicates significant proteinuria, suggesting potential kidney damage or conditions such as glomerulonephritis, diabetic nephropathy, or hypertensive nephrosclerosis. Conversely, a low or normal UPCR suggests healthy kidney function with minimal protein leakage.</p><p>The UPCR is advantageous because it eliminates the need for a 24-hour urine collection, which can be cumbersome and error-prone. Instead, it uses a random urine sample, providing a quick and reliable assessment. Monitoring the UPCR helps clinicians evaluate the severity of kidney disease, guide treatment decisions, and track the effectiveness of therapeutic interventions, ultimately aiding in the management and prevention of chronic kidney disease complications.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-13 05:32:19', '2024-07-13 05:32:19', NULL, 0),
(40, 24, 'GCT - Glucose Challenge Test ( Fasting + 2 hours )', 'EXP0040', '899', '499', 'Same day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Glucose Challenge Test (GCT) is a screening test for gestational diabetes, typically conducted between 24 and 28 weeks of pregnancy. The fasting GCT involves measuring a woman\'s blood glucose level after an overnight fast. After the initial blood draw, she consumes a glucose solution, and her blood is tested again two hours later.\r\n This \"2-hour\" GCT assesses how her body processes sugar over time. Elevated glucose levels at either point can indicate gestational diabetes, prompting further diagnostic testing and management to ensure maternal and fetal health.', 'Glucose', '<p>The Glucose Challenge Test (GCT) is a preliminary screening tool for gestational diabetes, typically administered between the 24th and 28th weeks of pregnancy. It evaluates how a pregnant woman\'s body processes sugar, helping to identify those at risk for gestational diabetes. The fasting GCT involves two main steps. First, the patient undergoes an initial blood draw after fasting overnight, which measures her baseline blood glucose level. This fasting period is essential as it provides an accurate assessment of her body\'s glucose regulation without the influence of recent food intake.</p><p>After the initial blood sample, the patient drinks a glucose-rich solution. Exactly two hours later, a second blood sample is taken. This 2-hour post-glucose measurement assesses how effectively her body metabolizes the sugar load. Elevated glucose levels at either the fasting or 2-hour mark can indicate a potential problem with glucose metabolism, suggesting gestational diabetes.</p><p>If the test results are above the normal range, further diagnostic testing, such as the Oral Glucose Tolerance Test (OGTT), may be required to confirm the diagnosis. Early detection and management of gestational diabetes are crucial for preventing complications such as high birth weight, preterm birth, and the development of type 2 diabetes later in life for both mother and child.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-13 05:54:19', '2024-07-20 17:27:46', NULL, 0),
(41, 2, 'G6PD ( Quantitative )', 'EXP0041', '1399', '699', 'Within 2 days', 'Fasting not required', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The G6PD test is a blood test that measures the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD), an enzyme found in red blood cells. This enzyme is essential for proper red blood cell function. A deficiency in G6PD can lead to the premature destruction of red blood cells, causing a condition known as hemolytic anemia.\r\n\r\nDoctors recommend this test if they suspect an individual may have a G6PD deficiency, particularly if there is a family history of the condition. People with G6PD deficiency need to avoid certain medications, foods, and infections that can trigger the breakdown of red blood cells.\r\n\r\nDuring the test, a blood sample is taken using a needle, which is then sent to a laboratory for analysis. The results typically take a few days to come back. Based on the results, doctors can provide appropriate treatment or advice to manage the condition.', NULL, '<p>Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD) is an enzyme crucial for the proper functioning of red blood cells. It plays a vital role in protecting these cells from oxidative damage by maintaining the levels of reduced glutathione, an antioxidant. G6PD deficiency is a genetic disorder caused by mutations in the G6PD gene, located on the X chromosome. This deficiency is particularly prevalent in people of African, Mediterranean, Middle Eastern, and Southeast Asian descent.</p><p>Individuals with G6PD deficiency have lower levels of the enzyme, making their red blood cells more susceptible to oxidative stress. Certain triggers, such as infections, certain foods (like fava beans), and specific medications (such as some antibiotics and antimalarials), can cause the red blood cells to break down prematurely. This breakdown leads to hemolytic anemia, characterized by symptoms such as fatigue, jaundice, dark urine, and shortness of breath.</p><p>The condition is often diagnosed through a blood test that measures the G6PD enzyme levels. Management involves avoiding known triggers and, in some cases, taking medications to treat or prevent hemolytic episodes. While G6PD deficiency is usually manageable, severe cases may require medical intervention, such as blood transfusions, during acute hemolytic crises. Genetic counseling is also recommended for affected families to understand the inheritance patterns and risks for future generations.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-13 05:58:20', '2024-07-13 05:59:02', NULL, 0),
(42, 2, 'Pro calcitonin', 'EXP0042', '3000', '1599', 'Same day', 'Fasting not required', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The procalcitonin test is used to detect and monitor severe bacterial infections such as sepsis. It measures levels of procalcitonin, a protein that rises significantly during bacterial infections but remains low in viral infections and non-infectious conditions. Elevated procalcitonin levels indicate a higher likelihood of a bacterial infection, guiding doctors in timely and appropriate antibiotic therapy. This test helps in distinguishing bacterial infections from other causes of illness, aiding in more effective treatment decisions and reducing unnecessary antibiotic use, which is crucial for patient care and antibiotic stewardship efforts to combat antibiotic resistance.', NULL, '<p>Procalcitonin is a protein produced by cells in the body, primarily the thyroid gland, in response to bacterial infections. Normally, procalcitonin levels in the blood are very low. However, during severe bacterial infections, especially those leading to sepsis, the body releases increased amounts of procalcitonin into the bloodstream.</p><p>The procalcitonin test is used as a diagnostic tool to differentiate between bacterial infections and other causes of illness, such as viral infections or inflammatory conditions. Elevated procalcitonin levels suggest a higher likelihood of a bacterial infection, prompting doctors to consider antibiotic treatment promptly. This is crucial because timely administration of antibiotics can significantly improve patient outcomes in bacterial infections.</p><p>Moreover, the procalcitonin test helps healthcare providers in antibiotic stewardship efforts. By identifying patients who truly need antibiotics based on bacterial infection indicators like procalcitonin levels, unnecessary antibiotic use can be minimized. This approach is important for combating antibiotic resistance, a global health concern where bacteria develop resistance to antibiotics over time due to overuse and misuse.</p><p>In summary, the procalcitonin test plays a vital role in clinical decision-making, guiding appropriate antibiotic therapy and supporting efforts to optimize patient care while combating antibiotic resistance.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-13 06:03:54', '2024-07-13 06:03:54', NULL, 0),
(43, 6, 'Anti HBc- Total, Hepatitis B Core - Total Anyibodies', 'EXP0043', '1599', '899', 'Within 2 days', 'Fasting not required', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Hepatitis B core antibody total (anti-HBc total) is an important marker used in the diagnosis of Hepatitis B virus (HBV) infection. It detects antibodies that are produced in response to the core antigen of the virus. The presence of anti-HBc total indicates either current or past infection with HBV, regardless of whether the infection has resolved or become chronic. \r\n\r\nThis antibody is typically detectable shortly after exposure to HBV and remains present for life, providing lifelong immunity in those who have cleared the virus. In chronically infected individuals, anti-HBc total is also present alongside other markers like HBsAg (surface antigen) and anti-HBs (surface antibody).\r\n\r\nThe test helps in determining the stage and immune status of HBV infection, guiding healthcare providers in managing patient care and vaccination strategies. Interpretation of results requires consideration of additional HBV markers to differentiate between acute, resolved, chronic, or vaccinated states.', NULL, '<p>Hepatitis B core total antibody (anti-HBc total) is a crucial immunological marker used in diagnosing and understanding Hepatitis B virus (HBV) infection. This antibody detects the presence of antibodies against the core antigen of the HBV, indicating exposure to the virus at some point in the past. Unlike specific markers that indicate acute or chronic infection, anti-HBc total remains detectable for life once produced, serving as a reliable indicator of past HBV exposure.</p><p>The presence of anti-HBc total can signify several scenarios:<br>1. **Past Infection**: In individuals who have resolved an HBV infection, anti-HBc total is usually present. This suggests that the immune system has successfully cleared the virus, although the individual may still have antibodies as a memory of the infection.</p><p>2. **Chronic Infection**: Anti-HBc total may also be present in chronically infected individuals, along with other markers like HBsAg (surface antigen) and possibly anti-HBs (surface antibody). Chronic infection occurs when the virus persists in the body for six months or longer.</p><p>3. **Vaccination**: In vaccinated individuals, anti-HBc total is generally absent unless there has been exposure to HBV. Vaccination stimulates the production of antibodies against HBsAg (anti-HBs), which provides protection against future infection.</p><p>Healthcare providers use anti-HBc total alongside other HBV markers to interpret a patient\'s hepatitis B status accurately. It helps differentiate between acute, resolved, chronic, or vaccinated states, guiding clinical management and vaccination strategies. Understanding the presence or absence of anti-HBc total is crucial for determining immune status, assessing the risk of re-infection or transmission, and planning appropriate interventions to manage hepatitis B effectively.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-13 06:10:12', '2024-07-31 12:51:13', NULL, 0),
(44, 6, 'Parietal cell Antibody', 'EXP0044', '3200', '1899', 'Within 2 days', 'Fasting not required', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Parietal Cell Antibody (PCA) test detects antibodies directed against parietal cells, which are found in the lining of the stomach. These antibodies are primarily associated with autoimmune conditions such as autoimmune gastritis and pernicious anemia. Parietal cells produce intrinsic factor, essential for vitamin B12 absorption. Autoimmune gastritis can lead to vitamin B12 deficiency due to impaired intrinsic factor production. The PCA test helps diagnose autoimmune gastritis and pernicious anemia, guiding appropriate treatment to manage symptoms and prevent complications associated with vitamin B12 deficiency.', NULL, '<p>The Parietal Cell Antibody (PCA) test is a blood test used to detect antibodies that target parietal cells, which are found in the lining of the stomach. These antibodies are primarily associated with autoimmune conditions, particularly autoimmune gastritis and pernicious anemia. Parietal cells play a crucial role in producing intrinsic factor, a protein necessary for the absorption of vitamin B12 in the intestine. Autoimmune gastritis can lead to the destruction of parietal cells, reducing intrinsic factor production and subsequently causing vitamin B12 deficiency.</p><p>The PCA test is recommended by doctors when there is suspicion of autoimmune gastritis or pernicious anemia based on clinical symptoms and other diagnostic findings. It helps confirm the presence of antibodies directed against parietal cells, indicating autoimmune activity against these cells. Elevated levels of PCA are indicative of autoimmune gastritis, which may progress to pernicious anemia if not treated promptly.</p><p>Diagnosing autoimmune gastritis early through PCA testing is crucial as it allows for timely intervention to prevent complications associated with vitamin B12 deficiency, such as anemia and neurological problems. Treatment often involves vitamin B12 supplementation and sometimes lifelong monitoring to manage symptoms and prevent long-term complications.</p><p>In summary, the PCA test plays a vital role in diagnosing autoimmune gastritis and pernicious anemia, guiding appropriate treatment strategies to alleviate symptoms and improve patient outcomes. Regular monitoring may be necessary to assess response to treatment and ensure adequate management of autoimmune conditions affecting parietal cells.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-13 06:21:29', '2024-07-13 06:21:29', NULL, 0),
(45, 6, 'Parietal Cell Antibody- ACPA', 'EXP0045', '3599', '1899', 'Within 2 days', 'Fasting not required', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Parietal Cell Antibody (PCA) test is a blood test that detects antibodies against the parietal cells lining the stomach. These cells produce intrinsic factor, essential for vitamin B12 absorption. The presence of these antibodies is associated with autoimmune conditions like autoimmune gastritis and pernicious anemia. Elevated PCA levels indicate that the immune system is attacking the stomach lining, potentially leading to vitamin B12 deficiency. This test helps diagnose these conditions, allowing doctors to develop appropriate treatment plans to manage symptoms and prevent complications.', NULL, '<p>The Parietal Cell Antibody (PCA) test is a diagnostic tool used to detect antibodies against the parietal cells in the stomach lining. Parietal cells are crucial for producing intrinsic factor, a protein necessary for the absorption of vitamin B12 in the small intestine. When the immune system mistakenly targets and destroys these cells, it can lead to autoimmune conditions such as autoimmune gastritis and pernicious anemia.</p><p>Autoimmune gastritis is characterized by chronic inflammation of the stomach lining, which can result in the destruction of parietal cells. This destruction reduces the production of intrinsic factor, leading to vitamin B12 deficiency. Pernicious anemia, a severe consequence of vitamin B12 deficiency, results in symptoms such as fatigue, weakness, pallor, and neurological issues.</p><p>The PCA test is typically ordered when a doctor suspects autoimmune gastritis or pernicious anemia based on symptoms and other clinical findings. A positive test indicates the presence of antibodies against parietal cells, confirming an autoimmune process. This information helps healthcare providers diagnose and manage the condition effectively.</p><p>Treatment for conditions identified by the PCA test often involves vitamin B12 supplementation to address the deficiency and manage symptoms. Early detection and treatment are crucial to prevent long-term complications associated with vitamin B12 deficiency, such as severe anemia and irreversible neurological damage. Regular monitoring and follow-up care are essential to ensure effective management and improve patient outcomes.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-13 17:19:21', '2024-07-13 17:19:21', NULL, 0),
(46, 6, 'Acetyl Choline Receptor Antibody - AChR-Ab', 'EXP0046', '3999', '2199', 'Within 6 Days', 'Fasting not required', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Acetylcholine Receptor Antibody (AChR-Ab) test is a blood test used to detect antibodies against acetylcholine receptors. These antibodies are associated with myasthenia gravis, an autoimmune disorder characterized by muscle weakness and fatigue. In myasthenia gravis, the immune system mistakenly attacks acetylcholine receptors at the neuromuscular junction, impairing muscle contraction. A positive AChR-Ab test indicates the presence of these antibodies, confirming the diagnosis. This test is crucial for diagnosing myasthenia gravis and guiding appropriate treatment to manage symptoms and improve the patient\'s quality of life.', NULL, '<p>The Acetylcholine Receptor Antibody (AChR-Ab) test is a specialized blood test used to detect the presence of antibodies that target acetylcholine receptors. These receptors are found at the neuromuscular junction, where nerve cells communicate with muscle cells to trigger muscle contractions. In myasthenia gravis, an autoimmune disorder, the immune system mistakenly produces antibodies that attack these receptors, leading to impaired communication between nerves and muscles.</p><p>This autoimmune attack results in the hallmark symptoms of myasthenia gravis, which include muscle weakness and fatigue. Commonly affected muscles include those controlling eye and eyelid movement, facial expression, chewing, swallowing, and speaking. In severe cases, the condition can impact respiratory muscles, posing significant health risks.</p><p>The AChR-Ab test is crucial for diagnosing myasthenia gravis. A positive result indicates the presence of acetylcholine receptor antibodies, confirming that the immune system is targeting these receptors. This confirmation allows healthcare providers to develop an appropriate treatment plan.</p><p>Treatment for myasthenia gravis often involves medications that enhance communication at the neuromuscular junction, such as acetylcholinesterase inhibitors, which increase the levels of acetylcholine. Immunosuppressive drugs may also be used to reduce the production of antibodies. In some cases, a surgical procedure called thymectomy, which removes the thymus gland, can be beneficial.</p><p>Early diagnosis through the AChR-Ab test is essential for effective management of myasthenia gravis. With timely and appropriate treatment, many individuals with this condition can lead active, productive lives. The test also aids in monitoring the disease\'s progression and the effectiveness of therapeutic interventions.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-13 17:24:36', '2024-07-13 17:24:36', NULL, 0),
(47, 2, '24 Hour Urine For Microalbumin', 'EXP0047', '500', '349', 'Same day', 'Not required', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A 24-hour urine test for microalbumin measures the amount of albumin, a type of protein, in the urine over a 24-hour period. Elevated levels of microalbumin in the urine can indicate early kidney damage, especially in individuals with diabetes or hypertension. Detecting microalbuminuria (small amounts of albumin in urine) helps in early intervention to prevent further kidney damage and manage underlying conditions. This test is crucial for monitoring kidney health and guiding treatment to protect renal function.', NULL, '<p>A 24-hour urine test for microalbumin is prescribed to evaluate kidney function, particularly to detect early signs of kidney damage. This test is especially important for patients with diabetes, hypertension, or other conditions that increase the risk of kidney disease. Here’s how and why the test is performed:</p><p>### **Purpose of the Test:**<br>1. **Early Detection:** Identify microalbuminuria, an early indicator of kidney damage, which can progress to more severe kidney disease if left untreated.<br>2. **Monitor Kidney Health:** Regular testing for patients with conditions like diabetes and hypertension to monitor kidney function and assess the effectiveness of treatments.<br>3. **Guide Treatment:** Adjust treatment plans based on test results to prevent further kidney damage.</p><p>### **Procedure:**<br>1. **Collecting Urine:** The patient will collect all urine produced over a 24-hour period. This involves:<br>&nbsp; - Using a provided container to collect urine.<br>&nbsp; - Discarding the first urine sample of the day.<br>&nbsp; - Collecting all subsequent urine, including the first sample the following morning.<br>&nbsp; - Storing the container in a cool place, such as a refrigerator, during the collection period.</p><p>2. **Submitting the Sample:** After the 24-hour period, the collected urine is submitted to a laboratory for analysis.</p><p>### **Interpretation of Results:**<br>- **Normal Levels:** Less than 30 mg of albumin per 24 hours.<br>- **Microalbuminuria:** 30-300 mg of albumin per 24 hours, indicating early kidney damage.<br>- **Macroalbuminuria:** More than 300 mg of albumin per 24 hours, suggesting more significant kidney damage.</p><p>### **Follow-Up:**<br>- **Lifestyle Modifications:** Recommendations may include dietary changes, regular exercise, and smoking cessation.<br>- **Medication Adjustments:** Adjustments to medications like ACE inhibitors or ARBs to protect kidney function.<br>- **Regular Monitoring:** Continued monitoring of kidney function through regular testing.</p><p>### **Conclusion:**<br>A 24-hour urine test for microalbumin is a valuable tool in the early detection and management of kidney disease. Early intervention based on test results can significantly improve patient outcomes by preventing further kidney damage and associated complications.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-13 17:28:53', '2024-07-13 17:28:53', NULL, 0);
