(137, NULL, 'Iron Profile Basic', 'EXP0137', '499', '350', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'An iron profile measures various aspects of iron metabolism in the body. It typically includes tests for serum iron (the amount of iron in the blood), ferritin (iron storage levels), transferrin (the protein that carries iron in the blood), and total iron-binding capacity (TIBC, the blood’s ability to bind and transport iron). This profile helps diagnose and monitor conditions like iron deficiency anemia, anemia of chronic disease, and iron overload disorders. It provides insights into how well iron is being absorbed and utilized.', 'Hair,Skin & Anxiety', '<p>The iron profile test is a comprehensive diagnostic tool used to assess various aspects of iron metabolism in the body. It is crucial for diagnosing and managing conditions related to iron balance, such as anemia, iron deficiency, and iron overload. The test typically comprises several key components:</p><p>1. **Serum Iron:** Measures the amount of free iron circulating in the blood. It provides insight into the current iron level but can fluctuate based on diet and other factors.</p><p>2.**Transferrin:** Evaluates the concentration of transferrin, a protein that transports iron in the bloodstream. Elevated transferrin levels are commonly seen in iron deficiency, whereas low levels may be indicative of chronic disease or malnutrition.</p><p>3. **Total Iron-Binding Capacity (TIBC):** Measures the maximum amount of iron that can be bound by transferrin. Increased TIBC is often associated with iron deficiency, while decreased TIBC may occur in chronic diseases or conditions affecting transferrin production.</p><p>4. **Transferrin Saturation:** This ratio, calculated from serum iron and TIBC, indicates the percentage of transferrin that is bound with iron. Low transferrin saturation suggests iron deficiency.</p><p>Together, these components provide a detailed overview of iron status, helping healthcare providers diagnose and manage conditions related to iron metabolism effectively.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-20 12:43:12', '2024-07-20 18:17:23', NULL, 0),
(138, NULL, 'Serum Iron', 'EXP0138', '290', '190', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Serum iron measures the concentration of free iron in the blood that is available for use by the body. This iron is bound to transferrin, a protein that transports iron to various tissues. The test helps assess iron levels and diagnose conditions such as iron deficiency anemia, chronic diseases, or iron overload disorders. Serum iron levels can fluctuate based on factors like diet, time of day, and recent iron intake, making it a part of a broader assessment of iron status.', NULL, '<p>Serum iron refers to the amount of free iron present in the liquid component of the blood, known as serum. Iron is a vital mineral that is crucial for various physiological functions, primarily for the formation of hemoglobin in red blood cells, which is essential for oxygen transport throughout the body. Serum iron is an important component of an iron profile, used to evaluate overall iron status and diagnose related disorders.</p><p>**Function and Measurement:**<br>Iron in the blood is primarily bound to a protein called transferrin, which transports iron to various tissues where it is needed for cellular functions, including the production of hemoglobin. The serum iron test measures the concentration of this iron in the blood. The measurement is typically expressed in micrograms per deciliter (µg/dL) or micromoles per liter (µmol/L).</p><p>**Clinical Significance:**<br>1. **Iron Deficiency Anemia:** Low serum iron levels can indicate iron deficiency anemia, a condition where there is insufficient iron to produce adequate amounts of hemoglobin, leading to symptoms like fatigue, weakness, and pallor.<br>2. **Iron Overload Disorders:** High serum iron levels may suggest conditions such as hemochromatosis or iron overload from repeated blood transfusions, where excessive iron accumulation can damage organs.<br>3. **Chronic Diseases:** Fluctuations in serum iron levels can be associated with chronic inflammatory diseases or infections that affect iron metabolism.</p><p>**Testing and Interpretation:**<br>The serum iron test is often performed alongside other tests, such as ferritin, transferrin, and total iron-binding capacity (TIBC), to provide a comprehensive assessment of iron status. Results are interpreted in the context of clinical symptoms and other diagnostic findings to accurately diagnose and manage iron-related conditions.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-20 13:07:38', '2024-07-20 13:07:38', NULL, 0),
(139, NULL, 'TIBC- Total Iron Binding Capacity', 'EXP0139', '290', '190', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Total Iron-Binding Capacity (TIBC) measures the maximum amount of iron that can be bound by proteins in the blood, primarily transferrin. It reflects the body\'s ability to transport iron. A high TIBC usually indicates iron deficiency, as the body produces more transferrin to capture available iron. Conversely, low TIBC can be associated with conditions like iron overload or chronic diseases, where transferrin production is reduced. TIBC is often measured alongside serum iron and ferritin to assess overall iron status.', NULL, '<p>Total Iron-Binding Capacity (TIBC) is a blood test that measures the maximum amount of iron that can be bound by proteins in the bloodstream, primarily transferrin. Transferrin is a protein produced by the liver that transports iron throughout the body. TIBC reflects the ability of transferrin to bind and transport iron, providing insights into the body’s iron status.</p><p>The TIBC test is used to evaluate iron metabolism and diagnose iron-related disorders. It is often performed in conjunction with serum iron and ferritin tests to assess overall iron levels and determine the underlying cause of anemia or iron deficiency. A high TIBC typically indicates iron deficiency anemia, as the body produces more transferrin in response to low iron levels. Conversely, a low TIBC can suggest conditions such as iron overload (hemochromatosis), chronic inflammation, or liver disease, where transferrin production is reduced.</p><p>The TIBC test involves drawing a blood sample, which is then analyzed in a laboratory. Results are reported in micrograms per deciliter (µg/dL) and are interpreted alongside other iron studies to provide a comprehensive view of an individual\'s iron status and guide appropriate treatment strategies.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-20 13:11:37', '2024-07-20 13:11:37', NULL, 0),
(140, NULL, 'Helicobacter Pylori-H.Pylori IgA Antibodies', 'EXP0140', '2899', '1670', 'Fasting is not mandatory', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The H. pylori IgA antibody test measures the presence of IgA antibodies specific to *Helicobacter pylori* in the blood. This test helps diagnose an active or recent infection by detecting the immune response to the bacterium. Elevated IgA levels can indicate an ongoing H. pylori infection, which may be associated with conditions like peptic ulcers or chronic gastritis. It is used to assess infection status and guide appropriate treatment.', NULL, '<p>The H. pylori IgA antibody test is a diagnostic tool used to detect the presence of Immunoglobulin A (IgA) antibodies against *Helicobacter pylori* in the blood. *H. pylori* is a bacterium that infects the stomach lining and is linked to various gastrointestinal conditions, including peptic ulcers, chronic gastritis, and an increased risk of gastric cancer.</p><p>**Purpose and Function:**<br>The test measures the immune response to an active or recent *H. pylori* infection. IgA is one of the first antibodies produced by the immune system upon encountering the bacterium, making it a useful marker for detecting early infection. Elevated levels of IgA antibodies suggest the body\'s ongoing immune response to *H. pylori*, indicating a current or recent infection.</p><p>**Clinical Significance:**<br>1. **Diagnosis of Infection:** The H. pylori IgA antibody test helps diagnose an active *H. pylori* infection, especially in symptomatic individuals presenting with signs of peptic ulcers, dyspepsia, or gastritis.<br>2. **Monitoring Treatment:** Post-treatment, a decrease in IgA antibody levels can indicate successful eradication of the bacterium, although it may not be as commonly used for monitoring compared to other methods like the urea breath test or stool antigen test.<br>3. **Complementary Use:** This test is often used alongside other diagnostic methods, such as endoscopy, biopsy, or stool antigen tests, to confirm an *H. pylori* infection and guide appropriate treatment.</p><p>**Limitations:**<br>While the IgA antibody test is helpful in diagnosing active *H. pylori* infection, it may not distinguish between past and current infections due to the persistence of antibodies in the blood even after the infection has been treated. Therefore, it is usually interpreted in conjunction with clinical symptoms and other diagnostic tests.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-20 13:21:24', '2024-07-20 13:21:24', NULL, 0),
(141, NULL, 'Lipase', 'EXP0141', '780', '430', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A lipase test measures the level of lipase, an enzyme produced by the pancreas, in the blood. Lipase helps break down fats into fatty acids and glycerol. Elevated lipase levels can indicate pancreatic disorders such as acute or chronic pancreatitis, pancreatic cancer, or other conditions affecting the pancreas. The test is useful for diagnosing and monitoring these conditions, as well as assessing abdominal pain and digestive issues.', NULL, '<p>The lipase test measures the concentration of lipase, an enzyme primarily produced by the pancreas, in the blood. Lipase plays a crucial role in the digestion of dietary fats by breaking them down into fatty acids and glycerol, which can be easily absorbed by the intestines. In addition to the pancreas, smaller amounts of lipase are produced by the stomach and salivary glands.</p><p>Clinically, the lipase test is used to diagnose and monitor pancreatic disorders. Elevated levels of lipase in the blood can indicate acute or chronic pancreatitis, conditions characterized by inflammation of the pancreas. It can also suggest other pancreatic issues, such as pancreatic cancer or blockages in the pancreatic duct. High lipase levels may also be seen in cases of gastrointestinal diseases, kidney failure, or severe abdominal pain of unknown origin.</p><p>The test is typically performed by drawing a blood sample, which is then analyzed for lipase activity. Normal lipase levels can vary slightly between different laboratories, but significantly elevated levels generally warrant further investigation to identify the underlying cause. Monitoring lipase levels helps healthcare providers diagnose, manage, and treat conditions related to the pancreas, improving patient outcomes.</p>', '<p>लिपेज़ टेस्ट रक्त में लिपेज़ की सांद्रता को मापता है, जो एक एंजाइम है जिसे मुख्य रूप से अग्न्याशय द्वारा उत्पादित किया जाता है। लिपेज़ आहार वसा के पाचन में महत्वपूर्ण भूमिका निभाता है, इन्हें फैटी एसिड और ग्लिसरॉल में तोड़ता है, जिन्हें आंतों द्वारा आसानी से अवशोषित किया जा सकता है। अग्न्याशय के अलावा, लिपेज़ की थोड़ी मात्रा पेट और लार ग्रंथियों द्वारा भी उत्पन्न होती है।</p><p>क्लिनिकली, लिपेज़ टेस्ट का उपयोग अग्न्याशय विकारों के निदान और निगरानी के लिए किया जाता है। रक्त में लिपेज़ के उच्च स्तर तीव्र या पुरानी अग्न्याशयशोथ का संकेत दे सकते हैं, जो अग्न्याशय की सूजन की स्थितियां होती हैं। यह अन्य अग्न्याशय के मुद्दों, जैसे अग्नाशयी कैंसर या अग्नाशयी नली में रुकावट का भी संकेत दे सकता है। उच्च लिपेज़ स्तर गैस्ट्रोइंटेस्टाइनल बीमारियों, गुर्दे की विफलता, या अज्ञात मूल के गंभीर पेट दर्द के मामलों में भी देखे जा सकते हैं।</p><p>यह परीक्षण आमतौर पर एक रक्त नमूना लेकर किया जाता है, जिसे फिर लिपेज़ गतिविधि के लिए विश्लेषित किया जाता है। सामान्य लिपेज़ स्तर विभिन्न प्रयोगशालाओं के बीच थोड़े भिन्न हो सकते हैं, लेकिन महत्वपूर्ण रूप से उच्च स्तर आमतौर पर अंतर्निहित कारण की पहचान के लिए आगे की जांच warrant करते हैं। लिपेज़ स्तरों की निगरानी स्वास्थ्य सेवा प्रदाताओं को अग्न्याशय से संबंधित स्थितियों का निदान, प्रबंधन और उपचार करने में मदद करती है, जिससे रोगियों के परिणामों में सुधार होता है।</p>', '2024-07-20 13:37:20', '2024-07-20 13:37:20', NULL, 0),
(142, NULL, 'Lipoprotein A-LPA', 'EXP0142', '1470', '790', 'Next day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A lipoprotein test measures the levels of lipoproteins in the blood. Lipoproteins are molecules that transport cholesterol and triglycerides through the bloodstream. This test typically includes measurements of low-density lipoprotein (LDL), high-density lipoprotein (HDL), and sometimes very low-density lipoprotein (VLDL). It helps assess the risk of cardiovascular diseases, such as heart disease and stroke, by evaluating cholesterol levels and their distribution within different types of lipoproteins.', NULL, '<p>A lipoprotein test, also known as a lipid panel or lipid profile, measures the levels of specific lipoproteins in the blood. Lipoproteins are complex particles composed of lipids (fats) and proteins that transport cholesterol and triglycerides through the bloodstream. The test typically includes measurements of:</p><p>1. **Low-Density Lipoprotein (LDL)**: Often referred to as \"bad\" cholesterol, high levels of LDL can lead to plaque buildup in arteries, increasing the risk of heart disease and stroke.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>2. **High-Density Lipoprotein (HDL)**: Known as \"good\" cholesterol, HDL helps remove cholesterol from the bloodstream, reducing the risk of cardiovascular diseases.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>3. **Total Cholesterol**: The sum of LDL, HDL, and VLDL (very low-density lipoprotein) levels.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>4. **Triglycerides**: A type of fat found in the blood; high levels can increase the risk of heart disease.</p><p>The lipoprotein test is used to assess the risk of cardiovascular diseases by evaluating cholesterol levels and their distribution among different types of lipoproteins. It helps guide dietary, lifestyle, and medication interventions to manage cholesterol levels and reduce the risk of heart disease and related conditions. The test is typically performed through a blood sample, often after fasting for 9-12 hours.</p>', '<p>लिपोप्रोटीन जटिल कण होते हैं जिनमें वसा (लिपिड) और प्रोटीन होते हैं जो रक्तप्रवाह में कोलेस्ट्रॉल और ट्राइग्लिसराइड्स को ले जाते हैं।&nbsp;<br>लिपोप्रोटीन परीक्षण का उपयोग हृदय संबंधी बीमारियों के जोखिम का आकलन करने के लिए किया जाता है, जिसमें कोलेस्ट्रॉल स्तर और उनके विभिन्न प्रकार के लिपोप्रोटीन में वितरण को देखा जाता है। यह परीक्षण आहार, जीवनशैली, और दवा हस्तक्षेप को मार्गदर्शित करने में मदद करता है ताकि कोलेस्ट्रॉल स्तर को प्रबंधित किया जा सके और हृदय रोग और संबंधित स्थितियों के जोखिम को कम किया जा सके। परीक्षण सामान्यतः एक रक्त नमूने के माध्यम से किया जाता है, जो अक्सर 9-12 घंटे की उपवास के बाद लिया जाता है।</p>', '2024-07-20 13:43:28', '2024-07-20 13:43:28', NULL, 0),
(143, NULL, 'Lithium', 'EXP0143', '850', '499', 'Next day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A lithium test measures the concentration of lithium in the blood. Lithium is a medication used primarily to treat bipolar disorder. This test helps ensure that lithium levels stay within the therapeutic range, as both low and high levels can lead to ineffective treatment or adverse effects. Regular monitoring helps manage dosing and prevent toxicity, ensuring the medication\'s efficacy while minimizing side effects. The test is crucial for maintaining proper lithium balance in patients undergoing lithium therapy.', NULL, '<p>The lithium test measures the concentration of lithium in the blood, specifically for patients undergoing lithium therapy. Lithium is a mood-stabilizing medication primarily used to treat bipolar disorder, a mental health condition characterized by extreme mood swings. It helps stabilize mood and prevent both manic and depressive episodes.</p><p>Lithium levels need to be carefully monitored because the difference between a therapeutic dose and a toxic dose is narrow. Too little lithium may not effectively control symptoms, while too much can lead to toxicity. Symptoms of lithium toxicity include nausea, tremors, confusion, and in severe cases, kidney damage or seizures.</p><p>The test is typically conducted by analyzing a blood sample, usually taken 12 hours after the last dose, to ensure accurate measurement of peak lithium levels. Monitoring is essential for adjusting dosages and ensuring the medication\'s effectiveness while avoiding adverse effects. Regular testing helps manage and adjust treatment plans to maintain therapeutic levels and prevent complications associated with improper lithium dosing.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-20 13:52:23', '2024-07-20 13:52:23', NULL, 0),
(144, NULL, 'Magnesium', 'EXP0144', '880', '390', 'Next day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The magnesium test measures the concentration of magnesium in the blood. Magnesium is an essential mineral involved in various bodily functions, including nerve and muscle function, blood sugar control, and bone health. It plays a crucial role in enzyme reactions and energy production. Abnormal levels of magnesium can indicate conditions such as kidney disease, diabetes, or gastrointestinal disorders. Low magnesium levels may cause muscle cramps, weakness, or irregular heartbeats, while high levels can lead to symptoms like nausea, confusion, and cardiac issues.', NULL, '<p>The magnesium test measures the concentration of magnesium in the blood, an essential mineral critical for numerous physiological functions. Magnesium is involved in over 300 enzymatic reactions in the body, contributing to energy production, protein synthesis, muscle and nerve function, and bone health. It helps regulate heart rhythm, blood sugar levels, and blood pressure. Magnesium is also vital for maintaining a healthy immune system.</p><p>The test is commonly used to diagnose and monitor conditions related to magnesium imbalance. Low magnesium levels (hypomagnesemia) can result from conditions such as gastrointestinal diseases, kidney disorders, or prolonged use of diuretics. Symptoms of low magnesium may include muscle cramps, weakness, and irregular heartbeats. Conversely, high magnesium levels (hypermagnesemia) can occur due to excessive supplementation or kidney dysfunction and may present with symptoms like nausea, confusion, or cardiac disturbances.</p><p>A blood sample is typically analyzed to measure serum magnesium levels. The test is useful in evaluating overall health, particularly in patients with conditions that affect magnesium balance. Regular monitoring helps guide appropriate treatment and dietary adjustments to manage magnesium levels and prevent complications.</p>', '<p>मैग्नीशियम शरीर में 300 से अधिक एंजाइमेटिक प्रतिक्रियाओं में शामिल होता है, जो ऊर्जा उत्पादन, प्रोटीन संश्लेषण, मांसपेशियों और तंत्रिका कार्य, और हड्डियों के स्वास्थ्य में योगदान करता है। यह हृदय की धड़कन, रक्त शर्करा स्तर, और रक्त दबाव को नियंत्रित करने में मदद करता है। मैग्नीशियम एक स्वस्थ प्रतिरक्षा प्रणाली के लिए भी महत्वपूर्ण है।</p><p>यह परीक्षण मैग्नीशियम असंतुलन से संबंधित स्थितियों का निदान और निगरानी करने के लिए आमतौर पर किया जाता है। कम मैग्नीशियम स्तर (हाइपोमैग्नीसेमिया) आंत्र संबंधी बीमारियों, गुर्दे की बीमारियों, या दीuretics के लंबे समय तक उपयोग के कारण हो सकता है। कम मैग्नीशियम के लक्षणों में मांसपेशियों में ऐंठन, कमजोरी, और असामान्य हृदय धड़कन शामिल हो सकते हैं। इसके विपरीत, उच्च मैग्नीशियम स्तर (हाइपरमैग्नीसेमिया) अत्यधिक सप्लीमेंटेशन या गुर्दे की समस्याओं के कारण हो सकता है और इसके लक्षणों में उल्टी, भ्रम, या हृदय संबंधी परेशानियाँ शामिल हो सकती हैं।</p>', '2024-07-20 13:57:00', '2024-07-20 13:58:49', NULL, 0),
(145, NULL, 'Phosphorus Calcium & Uric acid', 'EXP0145', '799', '399', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Phosphorus, calcium, and uric acid are vital substances measured in blood tests to assess various health conditions. \r\n\r\n- **Phosphorus:** Important for bone health and energy production.\r\n- **Calcium:** Crucial for bone strength, muscle function, and nerve signaling.\r\n- **Uric Acid:** A waste product from purine metabolism; high levels can indicate gout or kidney stones.\r\n\r\nThese tests help diagnose and manage conditions like bone disorders, kidney disease, and metabolic issues.', 'Teeth,healthy Bones & joint pain', NULL, NULL, '2024-07-20 17:53:33', '2024-07-20 17:53:33', NULL, 0),
(146, NULL, 'Alkaline phosphotase & protein', 'EXP0146', '580', '330', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '**Alkaline Phosphatase (ALP):** ALP is an enzyme found in various tissues, especially the liver, bones, and bile ducts. Elevated ALP levels can indicate liver disease, bone disorders, or bile duct obstruction. Low levels might suggest malnutrition or certain genetic conditions.\r\n\r\n**Protein:** Total protein test measures the amount of protein in the blood, including albumin and globulin. It helps assess nutritional status, liver and kidney function, and various medical conditions. Abnormal protein levels can indicate liver disease, kidney disease, or inflammatory conditions. \r\n\r\nThese tests are crucial for diagnosing and monitoring various health conditions.', 'Bone development', NULL, NULL, '2024-07-20 18:00:36', '2024-07-20 18:00:36', NULL, 0),
(147, NULL, 'Urine R/M - UTI detailed', 'EXP0147', '199', '99', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A Urine Routine Examination (Urine RM) is a common diagnostic test that evaluates various components of a urine sample. It typically includes:\r\n\r\n1. **Physical Examination:** Analyzes color, clarity, and specific gravity.\r\n2. **Chemical Examination:** Tests for pH, protein, glucose, ketones, bilirubin, urobilinogen, nitrites, and leukocyte esterase.\r\n3. **Microscopic Examination:** Detects cells, bacteria, crystals, and casts.\r\n\r\nThis test helps diagnose urinary tract infections, kidney disease, diabetes, liver conditions, and other medical issues.', 'Pus cells & bacteria', NULL, NULL, '2024-07-20 18:02:42', '2024-07-20 18:02:42', NULL, 0),
(148, NULL, 'Full Body Health Diagnostic :- Package 3', 'EXP0148', '4400', '1499', 'Same day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Package 3', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-20 18:27:03', '2024-07-20 19:37:05', NULL, 0),
(149, NULL, 'Electrolytes Profile', 'EXP0149', '899', '499', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Sodium,potassium & chloride', 'Electrolytes Imbalance', NULL, NULL, '2024-07-20 19:05:27', '2024-07-20 19:05:27', NULL, 0),
(150, NULL, 'Full  Body Health diagnostic :- Package 2', 'EXP0150', '3400', '950', 'Same day', 'Overnight fasting go 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Package 2', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-20 19:42:43', '2024-07-20 19:43:14', NULL, 0),
(151, NULL, 'RMA - Rapid Malaria Antigen PV & PF', 'EXP0151', '580', '299', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A rapid malaria antigen test detects specific proteins produced by malaria parasites in a patient\'s blood. It\'s a quick and simple diagnostic tool that provides results in 15-30 minutes. The test uses a small blood sample, typically obtained via finger prick, which is applied to a test strip or cassette. This method is particularly useful in areas with limited laboratory infrastructure, enabling timely diagnosis and treatment, thus reducing the burden of malaria, especially in resource-limited settings.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-22 18:06:24', '2024-07-22 18:06:24', NULL, 0),
(152, NULL, 'Malaria Parasite Slide ( MP slide )', 'EXP0152', '299', '130', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The malaria parasite slide test, or microscopic examination, is a traditional method for diagnosing malaria. It involves collecting a blood sample, usually via finger prick, and spreading it on a glass slide to create a blood smear. The smear is stained using Giemsa or other specific stains, which highlight the malaria parasites within red blood cells. A trained laboratory technician then examines the stained smear under a microscope to identify and quantify the presence of malaria parasites. This method is considered the gold standard for malaria diagnosis due to its high sensitivity and specificity. It allows for the identification of the malaria species and the determination of parasite density, which are crucial for appropriate treatment and monitoring. However, it requires skilled personnel and proper laboratory facilities.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-22 18:08:51', '2024-07-22 18:08:51', NULL, 0),
(153, NULL, 'Phosphorus', 'EXP0153', '350', '199', 'Same day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A phosphorus test measures the amount of phosphorus in the blood, an essential mineral involved in various bodily functions. Phosphorus works in tandem with calcium to build and maintain strong bones and teeth. It is also crucial for energy production, as it forms part of ATP (adenosine triphosphate), the molecule that stores and releases energy in cells. Additionally, phosphorus plays a role in the synthesis of DNA and RNA, the regulation of acid-base balance, and the proper functioning of muscles and nerves.\r\n\r\nThe test is often ordered to evaluate kidney function since the kidneys regulate phosphorus levels in the blood. It can help diagnose conditions like kidney disease, bone disorders, malnutrition, and issues with calcium metabolism. Monitoring phosphorus levels is particularly important for patients with chronic kidney disease or those undergoing dialysis.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-22 18:20:29', '2024-07-22 18:20:29', NULL, 0),
(154, NULL, 'MPO- ANCA ( P-ANCA )', 'EXP0154', '2480', '1299', 'Next day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A P-ANCA (Perinuclear Anti-Neutrophil Cytoplasmic Antibodies) test measures the presence of specific autoantibodies that target proteins in the cytoplasm of neutrophils, a type of white blood cell. These autoantibodies are often associated with autoimmune vasculitis, particularly microscopic polyangiitis and ulcerative colitis. The test helps in diagnosing and monitoring these autoimmune conditions by detecting the characteristic antibodies that indicate inflammation of blood vessels. It aids in distinguishing between different types of vasculitis and related disorders.', NULL, '<p>The P-ANCA (Perinuclear Anti-Neutrophil Cytoplasmic Antibodies) test is a blood test used to detect the presence of specific autoantibodies that target antigens in the perinuclear region of neutrophils, a type of white blood cell. These autoantibodies are often found in individuals with certain autoimmune diseases, particularly those affecting small blood vessels.</p><p>The P-ANCA test is commonly used in the diagnosis and monitoring of autoimmune vasculitis, such as microscopic polyangiitis, and other conditions like ulcerative colitis. In these diseases, the body\'s immune system mistakenly attacks its own blood vessels, leading to inflammation and damage. The presence of P-ANCA helps differentiate these conditions from other types of vasculitis and related disorders.</p><p>The test involves taking a blood sample and analyzing it in a laboratory for the characteristic antibodies. Positive results, along with clinical symptoms and other diagnostic tests, assist healthcare providers in confirming the diagnosis and guiding treatment decisions.</p>', '<p>P-ANCA (Perinuclear Anti-Neutrophil Cytoplasmic Antibodies) परीक्षण एक रक्त परीक्षण है जो न्यूट्रोफिल्स, एक प्रकार के श्वेत रक्त कोशिका, के पेरिन्यूक्लियर क्षेत्र में एंटीजन को लक्षित करने वाले विशिष्ट ऑटोएंटीबॉडी की उपस्थिति का पता लगाने के लिए उपयोग किया जाता है। ये ऑटोएंटीबॉडी अक्सर उन व्यक्तियों में पाए जाते हैं जिनमें कुछ ऑटोइम्यून बीमारियाँ होती हैं, विशेष रूप से वे जो छोटी रक्त वाहिकाओं को प्रभावित करती हैं।</p><p>P-ANCA परीक्षण का उपयोग आमतौर पर ऑटोइम्यून वास्कुलिटिस, जैसे माइक्रोस्कोपिक पॉलीएंजाइटिस, और अन्य स्थितियों जैसे अल्सरेटिव कोलाइटिस के निदान और निगरानी में किया जाता है। इन बीमारियों में, शरीर की प्रतिरक्षा प्रणाली गलती से अपनी रक्त वाहिकाओं पर हमला करती है, जिससे सूजन और क्षति होती है। P-ANCA की उपस्थिति इन स्थितियों को अन्य प्रकार के वास्कुलिटिस और संबंधित विकारों से अलग करने में मदद करती है।</p><p>परीक्षण में रक्त का नमूना लिया जाता है और प्रयोगशाला में विशेष एंटीबॉडी के लिए इसका विश्लेषण किया जाता है। सकारात्मक परिणाम, नैदानिक लक्षणों और अन्य नैदानिक परीक्षणों के साथ मिलकर, स्वास्थ्य सेवा प्रदाताओं को निदान की पुष्टि करने और उपचार के निर्णय लेने में मदद करते हैं।</p>', '2024-07-22 18:27:20', '2024-07-22 18:27:20', NULL, 0),
(155, NULL, 'DHEA - dehydroepiandrosterone', 'EXP0155', '3990', '2230', 'Next day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A DHEA (Dehydroepiandrosterone) test measures the level of DHEA sulfate (DHEA-S) in the blood. DHEA is a hormone produced by the adrenal glands, playing a key role in the production of male and female sex hormones, including testosterone and estrogen. The test helps evaluate adrenal gland function and diagnose conditions related to hormone imbalances, such as adrenal tumors, adrenal insufficiency, and polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS). It is also used to monitor patients with these conditions.', NULL, '<p>DHEA (Dehydroepiandrosterone) is a steroid hormone produced primarily by the adrenal glands, with smaller amounts secreted by the ovaries and testes. It serves as a precursor to male and female sex hormones, including testosterone and estrogen. The DHEA test, specifically measuring DHEA sulfate (DHEA-S), evaluates the level of this hormone in the blood.</p><p>DHEA levels peak in early adulthood and gradually decline with age. Measuring DHEA-S is useful in assessing adrenal gland function and diagnosing various conditions related to hormone imbalances. Elevated DHEA-S levels may indicate adrenal tumors, congenital adrenal hyperplasia, or polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS). Conversely, low levels can suggest adrenal insufficiency, Addison\'s disease, or hypopituitarism.</p><p>The DHEA test is particularly valuable in evaluating symptoms such as hirsutism, infertility, amenorrhea, and early puberty. It helps healthcare providers determine the underlying cause of these symptoms and guide appropriate treatment strategies. The test involves a simple blood draw and is often used alongside other hormonal tests for a comprehensive assessment.</p>', '<p>DHEA (Dehydroepiandrosterone) एक स्टेरॉयड हार्मोन है जो मुख्य रूप से अधिवृक्क ग्रंथियों द्वारा उत्पन्न होता है, और कम मात्रा में अंडाशय और वृषण द्वारा स्रावित होता है। यह पुरुष और महिला सेक्स हार्मोन, जैसे टेस्टोस्टेरोन और एस्ट्रोजन, के अग्रदूत के रूप में कार्य करता है। DHEA परीक्षण, विशेष रूप से DHEA सल्फेट (DHEA-S) को मापता है, और रक्त में इस हार्मोन के स्तर का मूल्यांकन करता है।</p><p>DHEA स्तर युवावस्था में चरम पर होता है और उम्र के साथ धीरे-धीरे कम होता जाता है। DHEA-S को मापना अधिवृक्क ग्रंथि के कार्य का आकलन करने और हार्मोन असंतुलन से संबंधित विभिन्न स्थितियों का निदान करने में सहायक है। ऊंचे DHEA-S स्तर अधिवृक्क ट्यूमर, जन्मजात अधिवृक्क हाइपरप्लासिया, या पॉलीसिस्टिक अंडाशय सिंड्रोम (PCOS) का संकेत दे सकते हैं। इसके विपरीत, निम्न स्तर अधिवृक्क अपर्याप्तता, एडिसन रोग, या हाइपोपीट्यूटेरिज्म का सुझाव दे सकते &nbsp;है&nbsp;</p><p>DHEA परीक्षण हिर्सुटिज़्म, बांझपन, ऐमेनोरिया, और प्रारंभिक यौवन जैसे लक्षणों का मूल्यांकन करने में विशेष रूप से मूल्यवान है। यह स्वास्थ्य सेवा प्रदाताओं को इन लक्षणों के अंतर्निहित कारण का निर्धारण करने और उपयुक्त उपचार रणनीतियों को मार्गदर्शित करने में मदद करता है। इस परीक्षण में एक साधारण रक्त का नमूना लिया जाता है और व्यापक आकलन के लिए अक्सर अन्य हार्मोनल परीक्षणों के साथ उपयोग किया जाता है।</p>', '2024-07-22 18:34:56', '2024-07-22 18:36:14', NULL, 0),
(156, NULL, 'TPHA with Titee - Treponema Pallidum Hemagglutination', 'EXP0156', '990', '590', 'Next day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A TPHA (Treponema pallidum hemagglutination assay) with titer measures the concentration of antibodies against Treponema pallidum, the bacterium that causes syphilis. The test detects and quantifies the presence of these antibodies in the blood, indicating a past or current syphilis infection. The titer represents the dilution at which antibodies are still detectable, helping assess the severity and progression of the infection. High titers can suggest active infection or a recent infection, while declining titers may indicate successful treatment.', NULL, '<p>The TPHA (Treponema pallidum hemagglutination assay) with titer is a blood test used to detect and measure antibodies against Treponema pallidum, the bacterium responsible for syphilis. This assay is highly sensitive and specific for syphilis detection. During the test, red blood cells coated with antigens are mixed with the patient\'s serum. If antibodies against Treponema pallidum are present, they will cause agglutination (clumping) of the red blood cells.</p><p>The titer represents the highest dilution of the patient\'s serum at which agglutination is still observable. It quantifies the concentration of these antibodies, providing information about the extent of the infection. High titers generally indicate an active or recent syphilis infection, while lower or declining titers may suggest resolution of the infection or a previous, treated infection. This test is often used to confirm syphilis diagnosis and monitor treatment efficacy over time.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-22 18:48:56', '2024-07-22 18:48:56', NULL, 0),
(157, NULL, 'Hepatitis C Virus- HCV Genotyping', 'EXP0157', '7000', '3350', 'Within 4 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'HCV genotyping measures the specific strain or type of Hepatitis C virus (HCV) present in a patient’s blood. This test identifies the viral genotype, which is crucial for determining the appropriate treatment regimen and predicting the likelihood of treatment success. HCV has several genotypes, each with multiple subtypes, and knowing the genotype helps tailor antiviral therapy and manage the disease effectively. This test is typically used to guide treatment decisions and monitor the response to therapy.', NULL, '<p>HCV genotype refers to the specific strain or type of Hepatitis C virus (HCV) identified in a patient. Hepatitis C is caused by the HCV, which has several distinct genotypes, each with multiple subtypes. Genotypes are classified based on genetic variations in the virus, and the most common genotypes are 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, and 6, with each having its own variations.</p><p>Determining the HCV genotype is crucial for guiding treatment decisions because different genotypes respond differently to antiviral therapies. For example, some genotypes may be more resistant to certain drugs, while others may respond better. Genotyping helps in selecting the most effective treatment regimen, predicting the likelihood of achieving a sustained viral response, and tailoring the duration of therapy. The test involves analyzing a blood sample to identify the specific HCV genotype and is an essential component of personalized treatment planning for Hepatitis C.</p>', '<p>HCV जीनोटाइप उस विशेष स्ट्रेन या प्रकार को संदर्भित करता है जो हेपेटाइटिस सी वायरस (HCV) में मरीज में पहचाना जाता है। हेपेटाइटिस सी HCV द्वारा होता है, जिसके कई विशिष्ट जीनोटाइप होते हैं, प्रत्येक के कई उपप्रकार होते हैं। जीनोटाइप वायरस में आनुवंशिक भिन्नताओं के आधार पर वर्गीकृत किए जाते हैं, और सबसे सामान्य जीनोटाइप 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, और 6 हैं, प्रत्येक के अपने-अपने विविधताएं होती हैं।</p><p>HCV जीनोटाइप का निर्धारण उपचार निर्णयों के मार्गदर्शन के लिए महत्वपूर्ण है, क्योंकि विभिन्न जीनोटाइप विभिन्न एंटिवायरल थेरापियों पर अलग-अलग प्रतिक्रिया करते हैं। उदाहरण के लिए, कुछ जीनोटाइप कुछ दवाओं के प्रति अधिक प्रतिरोधी हो सकते हैं, जबकि अन्य बेहतर प्रतिक्रिया कर सकते हैं। जीनोटाइपिंग सबसे प्रभावी उपचार योजना को चुनने, स्थायी वायरल प्रतिक्रिया प्राप्त करने की संभावना की भविष्यवाणी करने, और उपचार की अवधि को अनुकूलित करने में मदद करता है। परीक्षण में रक्त के नमूने का विश्लेषण करके विशेष HCV जीनोटाइप की पहचान की जाती है और यह हेपेटाइटिस सी के लिए व्यक्तिगत उपचार योजना का एक आवश्यक हिस्सा है।</p>', '2024-07-22 19:01:02', '2024-07-22 19:01:02', NULL, 0),
(158, NULL, 'Cardiolipin Antibody- ACL IgG', 'EXP0158', '1190', '690', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Cardiolipin antibodies measure the presence of autoantibodies against cardiolipin, a phospholipid component of cell membranes. These antibodies are often tested to diagnose antiphospholipid syndrome, an autoimmune disorder that increases the risk of blood clots, miscarriages, and other complications. Elevated levels of cardiolipin antibodies can indicate an increased risk of clotting disorders and help in evaluating the presence and severity of antiphospholipid syndrome. The test is used to guide treatment and monitor patients with suspected or confirmed autoimmune conditions.', NULL, '<p>Cardiolipin antibodies are autoantibodies that target cardiolipin, a phospholipid found in the inner mitochondrial membrane and in cell membranes. These antibodies are commonly associated with antiphospholipid syndrome (APS), an autoimmune condition that can lead to an increased risk of abnormal blood clotting, recurrent miscarriages, and other complications. In APS, the immune system mistakenly produces antibodies against cardiolipin, interfering with normal blood clotting processes.</p><p>The presence of cardiolipin antibodies in the blood is measured through a specific blood test. Elevated levels can help diagnose APS and assess the risk of thrombotic events. The test results are used in conjunction with clinical symptoms and other diagnostic criteria to guide treatment strategies and manage the risk of complications associated with APS.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-22 19:09:46', '2024-07-22 19:09:46', NULL, 0),
(159, NULL, 'Reticulocyte Count', 'EXP0159', '580', '290', 'Next day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A reticulocyte count measures the number of reticulocytes, which are immature red blood cells, in the blood. This test helps evaluate bone marrow function and red blood cell production. It is used to diagnose and monitor conditions such as anemia, bone marrow disorders, and the body\'s response to treatments like chemotherapy or erythropoietin therapy. High reticulocyte counts can indicate increased red blood cell production, while low counts may suggest bone marrow failure or insufficient production.', NULL, '<p>A reticulocyte count is a blood test that measures the number of reticulocytes, which are immature red blood cells newly released from the bone marrow into the bloodstream. This count is a crucial indicator of bone marrow function and the body’s ability to produce red blood cells.</p><p>Reticulocytes typically comprise about 0.5% to 2.5% of the total red blood cells in healthy individuals. The test is particularly useful in diagnosing and monitoring various conditions, such as anemia, bone marrow disorders, and the effectiveness of treatments like chemotherapy or erythropoietin therapy. Elevated reticulocyte counts can indicate increased red blood cell production in response to conditions like hemolytic anemia or blood loss, reflecting the bone marrow’s compensatory effort. Conversely, low reticulocyte counts may suggest bone marrow failure, aplastic anemia, or insufficient erythropoiesis.</p><p>By providing insights into red blood cell production and bone marrow health, the reticulocyte count helps healthcare providers diagnose underlying conditions, monitor treatment responses, and adjust therapeutic strategies accordingly.</p>', '<p>रेटिकुलोसाइट काउंट एक रक्त परीक्षण है जो रेटिकुलोसाइट्स की संख्या को मापता है, जो अपरिपक्व लाल रक्त कोशिकाएं होती हैं जिन्हें नई हड्डी मज्जा से रक्तप्रवाह में छोड़ा जाता है। यह गणना हड्डी मज्जा के कार्य और शरीर की लाल रक्त कोशिकाओं को उत्पन्न करने की क्षमता का एक महत्वपूर्ण संकेतक है।</p><p>स्वस्थ व्यक्तियों में रेटिकुलोसाइट्स आमतौर पर कुल लाल रक्त कोशिकाओं का लगभग 0.5% से 2.5% तक होते हैं। यह परीक्षण विभिन्न स्थितियों जैसे कि एनीमिया, हड्डी मज्जा विकारों, और कीमोथेरपी या एरिथ्रोपोइटिन थेरपी जैसे उपचारों की प्रभावशीलता के निदान और निगरानी में विशेष रूप से उपयोगी है। उच्च रेटिकुलोसाइट काउंट्स यह संकेत दे सकते हैं कि लाल रक्त कोशिकाओं का उत्पादन बढ़ गया है, जो हेमोलिटिक एनीमिया या रक्तस्राव जैसी स्थितियों के प्रति हड्डी मज्जा की प्रतिपूरक प्रतिक्रिया को दर्शाता है। इसके विपरीत, निम्न रेटिकुलोसाइट काउंट्स हड्डी मज्जा विफलता, एप्लास्टिक एनीमिया, या अपर्याप्त एरिथ्रोपोइएसिस का संकेत दे सकते हैं।</p><p>लाल रक्त कोशिका उत्पादन और हड्डी मज्जा स्वास्थ्य में अंतर्दृष्टि प्रदान करके, रेटिकुलोसाइट काउंट स्वास्थ्य सेवा प्रदाताओं को अंतर्निहित स्थितियों का निदान करने, उपचार प्रतिक्रियाओं की निगरानी करने, और चिकित्सीय रणनीतियों को समायोजित करने में मदद करता है।</p>', '2024-07-23 01:37:39', '2024-07-23 01:37:39', NULL, 0),
(160, NULL, 'Chikungunya Virus IgMAntibody Rapid', 'EXP0160', '880', '495', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A Chikungunya virus IgM rapid antibody test measures the presence of IgM antibodies against the Chikungunya virus in the blood. IgM antibodies are produced by the immune system shortly after infection, indicating a recent or acute infection. This rapid test helps diagnose Chikungunya fever, a mosquito-borne viral disease, in its early stages. By detecting IgM antibodies, healthcare providers can confirm an active Chikungunya infection and differentiate it from other similar illnesses, facilitating timely and appropriate treatment.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-23 07:18:23', '2024-07-23 07:18:23', NULL, 0),
(161, NULL, 'Cortisol-Morning', 'EXP0161', '999', '490', 'Same Day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A cortisol morning test measures the level of cortisol, a hormone produced by the adrenal glands, in the blood. Cortisol levels naturally peak in the early morning and decrease throughout the day. This test is typically performed in the morning to evaluate adrenal gland function and diagnose conditions such as Cushing\'s syndrome (high cortisol) or Addison\'s disease (low cortisol). By assessing morning cortisol levels, healthcare providers can better understand the body\'s stress response and hormonal balance.', NULL, '<p>Morning cortisol refers to the measurement of cortisol levels in the blood taken early in the morning, typically between 6:00 AM and 8:00 AM. Cortisol is a hormone produced by the adrenal glands that plays a crucial role in regulating metabolism, immune response, and the body\'s stress response. Cortisol levels follow a diurnal rhythm, peaking in the early morning and gradually decreasing throughout the day.</p><p>The morning cortisol test is used to assess adrenal gland function and diagnose disorders related to cortisol imbalance. Elevated morning cortisol levels can indicate conditions such as Cushing\'s syndrome, characterized by excessive cortisol production. Conversely, low morning cortisol levels may suggest adrenal insufficiency, as seen in Addison\'s disease. This test is essential for identifying and managing these conditions, helping healthcare providers tailor appropriate treatment plans based on the patient\'s hormonal profile and overall health status.</p>', '<p>सुबह का कॉर्टिसोल उस परीक्षण को संदर्भित करता है जिसमें सुबह के समय, आमतौर पर 6:00 AM से 8:00 AM के बीच, रक्त में कॉर्टिसोल स्तर को मापा जाता है। कॉर्टिसोल एक हार्मोन है जो एड्रिनल ग्रंथियों द्वारा उत्पादित होता है और यह मेटाबोलिज्म, प्रतिरक्षा प्रतिक्रिया, और शरीर के तनाव प्रतिक्रिया को नियंत्रित करने में महत्वपूर्ण भूमिका निभाता है। कॉर्टिसोल स्तर दिनभर में बदलता रहता है, सुबह के समय उच्चतम और दिनभर में धीरे-धीरे कम होता है।</p><p>सुबह का कॉर्टिसोल परीक्षण एड्रिनल ग्रंथि के कार्य का आकलन करने और कॉर्टिसोल असंतुलन से संबंधित विकारों का निदान करने के लिए उपयोग किया जाता है। उच्च सुबह के कॉर्टिसोल स्तर कशिंग सिंड्रोम जैसी स्थितियों का संकेत दे सकते हैं, जो अत्यधिक कॉर्टिसोल उत्पादन द्वारा चिह्नित होती है। इसके विपरीत, निम्न सुबह के कॉर्टिसोल स्तर एड्रिनल अपर्याप्तता का संकेत दे सकते हैं, जैसा कि एडिसन रोग में देखा जाता है। यह परीक्षण इन स्थितियों की पहचान और प्रबंधन के लिए महत्वपूर्ण है, जिससे स्वास्थ्य सेवा प्रदाता रोगी की हार्मोन प्रोफाइल और समग्र स्वास्थ्य स्थिति के आधार पर उचित उपचार योजनाओं को तैयार कर सकें।</p>', '2024-07-23 07:24:42', '2024-07-23 07:24:42', NULL, 0),
(162, NULL, 'Torch IgG', 'EXP0162', '1780', '799', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A TORCH IgG test measures the presence of IgG antibodies against a group of infectious agents: Toxoplasma, Rubella, Cytomegalovirus (CMV), and Herpes simplex virus (HSV). This test helps determine if a person has had a past infection or immunity to these pathogens, which can be particularly important for pregnant women. Detecting IgG antibodies indicates prior exposure and potential immunity, aiding in assessing the risk of congenital infections that could affect the fetus.', NULL, '<p>A TORCH IgG test is a blood test that measures the presence of IgG antibodies against a specific group of infections: Toxoplasma gondii (T), Rubella virus (R), Cytomegalovirus (C), and Herpes simplex virus (H). The acronym TORCH represents these pathogens, which can cause congenital infections if transmitted from a pregnant woman to her developing fetus. The presence of IgG antibodies indicates past exposure or immunity to these infections.</p><p>This test is particularly crucial for pregnant women, as it helps assess the risk of transmitting these infections to the fetus. A positive IgG result suggests that the individual has had a prior infection and may have developed immunity, reducing the risk of active infection during pregnancy. Conversely, a negative result indicates no prior exposure, and the person may be susceptible to these infections.</p><p>Understanding a patient’s IgG antibody status allows healthcare providers to take necessary precautions and provide appropriate care to prevent potential complications, such as birth defects or developmental issues, in the newborn.</p>', '<p>TORCH IgG परीक्षण एक रक्त परीक्षण है जो विशेष संक्रमणों के समूह के खिलाफ IgG एंटीबॉडी की उपस्थिति को मापता है: Toxoplasma gondii (T), Rubella virus (R), Cytomegalovirus (C), और Herpes simplex virus (H)। TORCH शब्द इन रोगजनकों का प्रतिनिधित्व करता है, जो गर्भवती महिला से उसके विकासशील भ्रूण को संक्रमित करने पर जन्मजात संक्रमण का कारण बन सकते हैं। IgG एंटीबॉडी की उपस्थिति इन संक्रमणों के खिलाफ पिछले संपर्क या प्रतिरक्षा का संकेत देती है।</p><p>यह परीक्षण गर्भवती महिलाओं के लिए विशेष रूप से महत्वपूर्ण है, क्योंकि यह भ्रूण को इन संक्रमणों के संचरण के जोखिम का आकलन करने में मदद करता है। सकारात्मक IgG परिणाम से पता चलता है कि व्यक्ति को पहले संक्रमण हुआ था और उसने प्रतिरक्षा विकसित की हो सकती है, जिससे गर्भावस्था के दौरान सक्रिय संक्रमण का जोखिम कम हो जाता है। इसके विपरीत, नकारात्मक परिणाम इंगित करता है कि कोई पिछला संपर्क नहीं हुआ है, और व्यक्ति इन संक्रमणों के प्रति संवेदनशील हो सकता है।</p><p>रोगी के IgG एंटीबॉडी की स्थिति को समझना स्वास्थ्य सेवा प्रदाताओं को आवश्यक सावधानियां बरतने और उचित देखभाल प्रदान करने की अनुमति देता है ताकि नवजात शिशु में जन्म दोष या विकास संबंधी समस्याओं जैसी संभावित जटिलताओं को रोका जा सके।</p>', '2024-07-23 07:32:16', '2024-07-23 07:32:16', NULL, 0);
